<h2>Models by Disease</h2>

<p>The core methodology uses gradient-boosted decision trees trained on routine CBC and CMP data from electronic health records. ColonFlag (AUC 0.82, deployed) and LungFlag (AUC 0.856, validated) serve as the two reference implementations, both developed using retrospective EHR data and externally validated across independent health systems. Click any disease below to view the published research.</p>

<h3>Cancers</h3>

<div class="disease-accordion">

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Colorectal Cancer <span class="status-deployed">DEPLOYED</span></summary>
<p>ColonFlag is the most mature algorithm in this program. It has been deployed in clinical settings in Israel, the United States, and the United Kingdom, with prospective validation at Maccabi Healthcare Services, Kaiser Permanente, and Geisinger confirming an eightfold improvement in cancer detection among flagged patients.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Kinar Y, et al. "Development and validation of a predictive model for detection of colorectal cancer in primary care by analysis of complete blood counts." <em>JAMIA</em> 2016;23(5):879–890. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/jamia/ocv195" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1093/jamia/ocv195</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Original ColonFlag derivation and binational validation using gradient boosting and random forest on 606,403 Israeli and 30,674 UK patients. AUC 0.82, detection maintained for CBCs taken two years before diagnosis.</em></p></li>
<li>Hornbrook MC, et al. "Early Colorectal Cancer Detected by Machine Learning Model Using Gender, Age, and Complete Blood Count Data." <em>Dig Dis Sci</em> 2017;62(10):2719–2727. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10620-017-4722-8" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1007/s10620-017-4722-8</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>US validation at Kaiser Permanente Northwest. AUC 0.80; tenfold higher risk of undiagnosed cancer at curable stages. 66% of flagged patients had no clinical suspicion at time of triggering blood test.</em></p></li>
<li>Goshen R, et al. "Computer-Assisted Flagging of Individuals at High Risk of Colorectal Cancer Using the ColonFlag Test." <em>JCO Clin Cancer Inform</em> 2018;2:1–8. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI.17.00130" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI.17.00130</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Prospective deployment at Maccabi on 79,671 patients. Among 254 high-risk individuals, 19 colorectal cancers (7.5%) and 15 non-colorectal cancers identified. Passive EHR integration requiring no new specimens or patient action.</em></p></li>
<li>Goldshtein I, et al. "Variations in hemoglobin before colorectal cancer diagnosis." <em>Eur J Cancer Prev</em> 2010;19(5):342–344. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20543703/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20543703/</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Hemoglobin declines ~4 years before diagnosis at 0.28 g/dL per 6-month period while remaining in normal range. Primary pre-diagnostic signal exploited by ColonFlag.</em></p></li>
<li>Virdee PS, et al. "The Full Blood Count Blood Test for Colorectal Cancer Detection: A Systematic Review, Meta-Analysis, and Critical Appraisal." <em>Cancers</em> 2020;12(9):2348. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3390/cancers12092348" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3390/cancers12092348</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Meta-analysis of 53 studies confirming 6 CBC components associated with colorectal cancer: decreased RBC, hemoglobin, MCV; increased RDW, WBC, platelets.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Lung Cancer <span class="status-validated">VALIDATED</span></summary>
<p>LungFlag has completed large-scale validation at Kaiser Permanente (AUC 0.856) and outperforms both USPSTF screening criteria and the PLCOm2012 risk model. Budget impact modeling projects net cost savings of $2.87 million over five years per health system. 65% of lung cancer patients do not meet current LDCT screening eligibility.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Gould MK, et al. "Machine Learning for Early Lung Cancer Identification Using Routine Clinical and Laboratory Data." <em>Am J Respir Crit Care Med</em> 2021;204(4):445–453. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1164/rccm.202007-2791OC" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1164/rccm.202007-2791OC</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>LungFlag XGBoost on 6,505 NSCLC cases and 189,597 controls. AUC 0.86 at 9–12 months pre-diagnosis, outperforming PLCOm2012 (AUC 0.79). Approved for UK CPRD validation.</em></p></li>
<li>Song B, et al. "Utility of Red Cell Distribution Width as a Diagnostic and Prognostic Marker in Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer." <em>Sci Rep</em> 2020;10(1):15717. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-020-72585-4" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-020-72585-4</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>RDW alone achieved AUC 0.753 for NSCLC detection. Mendelian randomization confirmed causal association (OR 1.11, P = 0.006).</em></p></li>
<li>Sanchez-Salcedo P, et al. "Exploring the Neutrophil/Lymphocyte and Platelet/Lymphocyte Ratios as Biomarkers for Lung Cancer Development." <em>Eur Respir J</em> 2015;46(Suppl 59):PA4241. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1183/13993003.congress-2015.PA4241" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1183/13993003.congress-2015.PA4241</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>NLR annual progression 2.56% vs 0.27% in controls; PLR 3.75% vs 0.33%. CBC captures temporal inflammatory signal years before diagnosis.</em></p></li>
<li>Yang HC, et al. "Age-Based Screening for Lung Cancer Surveillance in the US." <em>JAMA Netw Open</em> 2025;8(11):e2546222. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2024.56088" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2024.56088</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Only 35.1% of 997 lung cancer patients met USPSTF LDCT criteria. 65% excluded—disproportionately female and Asian. Documents the gap blood-based ML screening addresses.</em></p></li>
<li>Maraz A, et al. "Thrombocytosis Has a Negative Prognostic Value in Lung Cancer." <em>Anticancer Res</em> 2013;33(4):1725–1729. <a href="https://ar.iiarjournals.org/content/33/4/1725" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://ar.iiarjournals.org/content/33/4/1725</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Thrombocytosis in 17–29% of lung cancer cases. Supports systemic inflammatory blood signature.</em></p></li>
<li>Gould MK, et al. "Budget Impact Model for LungFlag." <em>J Clin Oncol</em> 2024;42(16_suppl):10534. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2024.42.16_suppl.10534" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2024.42.16_suppl.10534</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Projected 17 additional early-stage diagnoses/year, 22 fewer deaths, net savings of $2.87M over 5 years per health system.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Liver Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>LightGBM and random forest models have achieved AUC 0.87 to 0.894 using routine CBC and liver function panels, with the largest study covering 900,000+ individuals. FIB-4 trajectory over time provides the strongest individual predictive signal.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Kwok KN, et al. "Development of a novel routine blood-based AI model for hepatocellular carcinoma screening—a territory-wide study." <em>ESMO GIO</em> 2025;10:100241. <a href="https://www.esmogastro.org/article/S2949-8198(25)00110-4/fulltext" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.esmogastro.org/article/S2949-8198(25)00110-4/fulltext</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>LightGBM on CBC/LFT/RFT. AUC 0.894 (test), 0.871 (validation), outperforming AFP.</em></p></li>
<li>Clusmann J, et al. "Machine learning predicts liver cancer risk from routine clinical data." <em>medRxiv</em> 2024. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1101/2024.11.03.24316662" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1101/2024.11.03.24316662</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random forest on 900,000+ individuals from UK Biobank and NIH All of Us. AUC 0.88. Preprint.</em></p></li>
<li>Zhang Z, et al. "Value of GPR, APPRI and FIB-4 in the early diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma." <em>Jpn J Clin Oncol</em> 2024;54(2):129–136.<p class="ref-annotation"><em>FIB-4 achieved AUC 0.81; highest-quartile FIB-4 carried HR 18.58 in 44,215 participants.</em></p></li>
<li>Yeo YH, et al. "Dynamic FIB-4 Score Changes and HCC Risk in Patients with MASLD." <em>Liver Cancer</em> 2026. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1159/000550360" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1159/000550360</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>810,698 MASLD patients. Transition from low to high FIB-4 over 3 years predicted future HCC. Serial trajectory more powerful than single reading.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Gastric Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost (XHGC20) and GBDT models achieve AUC 0.89 to 0.91 using 20 routine hematological indicators. Iron-deficiency anemia is a documented precursor in a 122,502-patient German primary care study. Validation outside East Asian populations is a priority.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Ke X, et al. "Predicting early gastric cancer risk using machine learning." <em>Digit Health</em> 2024;10. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1177/20552076241240905" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1177/20552076241240905</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>XHGC20: validation AUC 0.901, test AUC 0.907, AUC 0.970 for tumor marker-negative patients.</em></p></li>
<li>Zhu SL, et al. "Application of machine learning in the diagnosis of gastric cancer." <em>PLOS One</em> 2020;15(12):e0244869. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0244869" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0244869</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>GBDT on 709 patients. AUC 0.91, sensitivity 87.0%, specificity 84.1%.</em></p></li>
<li>Fang T, et al. "Diagnostic Sensitivity of NLR and PLR in Early Diagnosis of Gastric Cancer." <em>J Immunol Res</em> 2020. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1155/2020/9146042" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1155/2020/9146042</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>NLR AUC 0.715, PLR AUC 0.707—both superior to CEA and CA19-9 for early-stage detection.</em></p></li>
<li>Krieg S, et al. "Association between iron deficiency anemia and subsequent stomach and colorectal cancer diagnosis in Germany." <em>J Cancer Res Clin Oncol</em> 2024;150(2):53. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00432-023-05534-z" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1007/s00432-023-05534-z</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>122,502 IDA patients; significant excess of subsequent gastric cancer. IDA on CBC as pre-diagnostic signal.</em></p></li>
<li>Aksoy EK, et al. "The importance of complete blood count parameters in the screening of gastric cancer." <em>Gastroenterol Rev</em> 2019;14(3):183–187. <a href="https://doi.org/10.5114/pg.2019.88167" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.5114/pg.2019.88167</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>NLR, PLR, MLR distinguish cancer from precancerous intestinal metaplasia.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Pancreatic Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost models exploiting glucose trajectory in new-onset diabetes patients achieve AUC 0.80–0.84, with detection windows of 2–3 years. The Optum EHR model identified 58% of late-stage patients a median of 24 months earlier.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Khan S, Bhushan B. "Machine Learning Predicts Patients With New-onset Diabetes at Risk of Pancreatic Cancer." <em>J Clin Gastroenterol</em> 2024;58(7):681–691. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/MCG.0000000000001897" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1097/MCG.0000000000001897</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.80, outperforming END-PAC (0.63) and Boursi (0.68).</em></p></li>
<li>Chen Q, et al. "Clinical Data Prediction Model to Identify Patients With Early-Stage Pancreatic Cancer." <em>JCO Clin Cancer Inform</em> 2021;5:279–287. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI.20.00137" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI.20.00137</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.84 on Optum EHR (3,322 early-stage, 25,908 late-stage). Detected 58% of late-stage patients 24 months earlier.</em></p></li>
<li>Tan PS, et al. "Temporality of body mass index, blood tests, comorbidities as early markers for pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma." <em>Gut</em> 2023;72(3):512–521. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/gutjnl-2021-326522" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1136/gutjnl-2021-326522</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>28,137 PDAC cases. HbA1c diverged 2–3 years before; liver enzymes rose 1 year before.</em></p></li>
<li>Sharma A, et al. "Fasting Blood Glucose Levels Provide Estimate of Duration and Progression of Pancreatic Cancer Before Diagnosis." <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2018;155(2):490–500. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2018.04.025" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2018.04.025</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>FBG diverged 30–36 months before diagnosis. Post-surgical resection improved FBG, confirming causal relationship.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Ovarian Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>A multicenter AI study across 11,000 patients achieved AUC 0.949 (general) and 0.968 (subtype-specific). Thrombocytosis on routine CBC carries a 23.3-fold increased risk.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Kawakami E, et al. "Application of AI for Preoperative Diagnostic and Prognostic Prediction in Epithelial Ovarian Cancer." <em>Clin Cancer Res</em> 2019;25(10):3006–3015. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-18-3378" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-18-3378</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random forest on 32 routine blood parameters. AUC 0.968 for cancer vs benign.</em></p></li>
<li>Cai G, et al. "AI-based models enabling accurate diagnosis of ovarian cancer using laboratory tests in China." <em>Lancet Digit Health</em> 2024;6(3):e176–e186. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S2589-7500(23)00245-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/S2589-7500(23)00245-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>11,000 patients, 20 AI classifiers, 52 lab variables. AUC 0.949 internal, 0.882–0.884 external.</em></p></li>
<li>Menon U, et al. "Risk Algorithm Using Serial Biomarker Measurements Doubles Screen-Detected Cancers." <em>J Clin Oncol</em> 2015;33(18):2062–2071. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2014.59.4945" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2014.59.4945</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>202,638 women. ROCA algorithm using serial CA-125 velocity outperformed single threshold.</em></p></li>
<li>Giannakeas V, Narod SA. "Incidence of Cancer Among Adults With Thrombocytosis in Ontario, Canada." <em>JAMA Netw Open</em> 2021;4(8):e2120633. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2021.20633" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2021.20633</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>23.3-fold increased ovarian cancer risk with thrombocytosis. Slow rise for 18 months, rapid rise in final 6 months.</em></p></li>
<li>Stone RL, et al. "Paraneoplastic Thrombocytosis in Ovarian Cancer." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2012;366(7):610–618. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1110352" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1110352</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Tumor-derived IL-6 causes thrombocytosis. Anti-IL-6 reduced platelet counts, confirming mechanistic basis.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Kidney Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>A random forest model on eight routine blood markers achieved AUC 0.932. UK Biobank prospective data confirms the pre-diagnostic signal. External validation and prospective testing remain outstanding.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Li H, et al. "Machine Learning Screening of Kidney Cancer: An Eight-Indicator Blood Test Panel." <em>Curr Oncol</em> 2022;29(12):9135–9149. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3390/curroncol29120715" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3390/curroncol29120715</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.932, sensitivity 88.2%, specificity 86.3% on 743 RCC patients and 500 controls.</em></p></li>
<li>He Q, et al. "Blood cell indices and inflammation-related markers with kidney cancer risk in UK Biobank." <em>Front Oncol</em> 2024;14:1366449. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3389/fonc.2024.1366449" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3389/fonc.2024.1366449</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>466,994 participants over 12.4 years. MCHC, RDW, PDW, SII as independent risk factors.</em></p></li>
<li>Zhou Y, et al. "Identifying opportunities for timely diagnosis of bladder and renal cancer via abnormal blood tests." <em>Br J Gen Pract</em> 2022;72(714):e19–e25. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3399/BJGP.2021.0282" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3399/BJGP.2021.0282</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Blood test abnormalities increased 6–8 months before kidney cancer diagnosis in 4,533 patients.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Myeloma <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>AdaBoost and random forest models achieve AUC 0.957–0.968. Pre-diagnostic hemoglobin decline begins 2–3 years before diagnosis, documented in a 1.1 million Scandinavian blood donor cohort.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Cai J, et al. "Construction of the prediction model for multiple myeloma based on machine learning." <em>Int J Lab Hematol</em> 2024;46(5):918–926. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/ijlh.14324" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1111/ijlh.14324</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random forest on 465 patients. Training AUC 0.956, test AUC 0.875.</em></p></li>
<li>Fan G, et al. "Routine blood biomarkers for the detection of multiple myeloma using machine learning." <em>Int J Lab Hematol</em> 2022;44(3):558–566. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/ijlh.13806" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1111/ijlh.13806</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AdaBoost AUC 96.8%, accuracy 92.6%. Highest-performing ML model across any cancer in the series.</em></p></li>
<li>Koshiaris C, et al. "Early detection of multiple myeloma in primary care using blood tests." <em>Br J Gen Pract</em> 2018;68(674):e586–e593. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3399/bjgp18X698357" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3399/bjgp18X698357</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>2,703 myeloma cases. Hemoglobin declined 3 years before; ESR elevated 2 years before (OR 5.7).</em></p></li>
<li>Edgren G, et al. "Pattern of declining hemoglobin concentration before cancer diagnosis." <em>Int J Cancer</em> 2010;127(6):1429–1436. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/ijc.25122" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1002/ijc.25122</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>1.1 million Scandinavian blood donors. Hemoglobin decline begins 3 years before myeloma—earliest among all cancers.</em></p></li>
<li>Kyle RA, et al. "A Long-Term Study of Prognosis in Monoclonal Gammopathy of Undetermined Significance." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2002;346(8):564–569. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa01133202" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa01133202</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>1,384 MGUS patients. 1% annual progression to myeloma. Protein gap on CMP as primary pre-clinical signal.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Leukemia <span class="status-validated">VALIDATED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost on VA data achieves AUC 0.87–0.96 for CML. Random forest on 1.09 million patients achieves AUC 0.92 for CLL. Among the closest to deployment readiness after ColonFlag and LungFlag.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Aoki J, et al. "Machine Learning Model Predicts Abnormal Lymphocytosis Associated With CLL." <em>JCO Clin Cancer Inform</em> 2025;9:e2400197. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI-24-00197" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1200/CCI-24-00197</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>1,090,707 patients over 7-year longitudinal CBC. AUC 0.92. Top features: lymphocyte count and slope, WBC trajectory.</em></p></li>
<li>Padmanabhan R, et al. "Machine Learning for Diagnosis and Screening of CLL Using Routine CBC Results." <em>Stud Health Technol Inform</em> 2023;305:279–282. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3233/SHTI230483" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3233/SHTI230483</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>XGBoost 98.62% accuracy on 11 CBC parameters alone.</em></p></li>
<li>Hauser RG, et al. "A Machine Learning Model to Predict Future Diagnosis of CML With Retrospective EHR Data." <em>Am J Clin Pathol</em> 2021;156(6):1142–1148. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1093/ajcp/aqab086" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1093/ajcp/aqab086</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>1,623 CML patients from VA. AUC 0.87–0.96 at diagnosis, 0.75–0.83 at 6 months before. Basophil percentage most informative.</em></p></li>
<li>Kuan JW, et al. "Systematic review of pre-clinical chronic myeloid leukaemia." <em>Int J Hematol</em> 2018;108(5):465–484. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s12185-018-2528-x" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1007/s12185-018-2528-x</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Basophil percentage diverges before leukocytosis reaches diagnostic thresholds. Earliest CBC marker for CML.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Lymphoma <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>ML model trained on 663,184 patients achieved AUC 0.84 for hematological malignancy prediction. Blood test activity increases more than 5 years before diagnosis—one of the longest pre-diagnostic windows.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Christensen M, et al. "Predicting Hematological Malignancies Using Complete Blood Cell Counts From Primary Care." <em>Hemasphere</em> 2023;7(Suppl):e72792be. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/01.HS9.0000977488.72792.be" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1097/01.HS9.0000977488.72792.be</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>663,184 patients. AUC 0.84 at 6 months, 0.85 with 5 years of CBC history.</em></p></li>
<li>Ahmed R, et al. "The Outcome of Hodgkin Lymphoma With Reference to Prognostic Markers." <em>Cureus</em> 2022;14(8):e28509. <a href="https://doi.org/10.7759/cureus.28421" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.7759/cureus.28421</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>LDH deranged in 51.6%, ESR elevated in 56.7% of Stage III HL at diagnosis.</em></p></li>
<li>Christensen ME, et al. "Blood sampling patterns in primary care change several years before a cancer diagnosis." <em>Acta Oncol</em> 2024;63:28559. <a href="https://doi.org/10.2340/1651-226X.2024.28559" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.2340/1651-226X.2024.28559</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Increased blood test activity 5+ years before hematological malignancy. Clinicians detected abnormal values without acting systematically.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Bladder Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>LightGBM on 1,336 patients achieved AUC 0.88–0.92 using standard CMP outputs. UK longitudinal data shows CBC inflection points 6–8 months pre-diagnosis.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Tsai IJ, et al. "Machine Learning in Prediction of Bladder Cancer on Clinical Laboratory Data." <em>Diagnostics</em> 2022;12(1):203. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3390/diagnostics12010203" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3390/diagnostics12010203</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.88–0.92. Top features: calcium, ALP, albumin, creatinine, ALT.</em></p></li>
<li>Zhou Y, et al. "Identifying opportunities for timely diagnosis of bladder and renal cancer via abnormal blood tests." <em>Br J Gen Pract</em> 2022;72(714):e19–e25. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3399/BJGP.2021.0282" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3399/BJGP.2021.0282</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>CBC inflection points 6–8 months pre-diagnosis in 32–45% of bladder cancer patients.</em></p></li>
<li>Watson J, et al. "Predictive value of inflammatory markers for cancer diagnosis in primary care." <em>Br J Cancer</em> 2019;120(11):1045–1051. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41416-019-0458-x" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41416-019-0458-x</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Raised CRP/ESR associated with 3.53% vs 1.50% one-year cancer incidence in 160,000 patients.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Breast Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>Largest CBC-based study (396,848 women) achieved modest AUC 0.64. Pre-diagnostic signal confirmed but discriminative performance lags behind other cancers. Longitudinal trajectory features expected to improve results.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Araujo DC, et al. "Unlocking the complete blood count as a risk stratification tool for breast cancer." <em>Sci Rep</em> 2024;14:10841. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-61215-y" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-61215-y</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Ridge regression on 396,848 women. AUC 0.64; high-risk 10% captured 19.8% of cancers.</em></p></li>
<li>Ethier JL, et al. "Prognostic role of neutrophil-to-lymphocyte ratio in breast cancer." <em>Breast Cancer Res</em> 2017;19:2. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s13058-016-0794-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1186/s13058-016-0794-1</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Elevated NLR associated with worse OS (HR 2.56), DFS (HR 1.74).</em></p></li>
<li>Nøst TH, et al. "Systemic inflammation markers and cancer incidence in the UK Biobank." <em>Eur J Epidemiol</em> 2021;36:841–848. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10654-021-00752-6" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1007/s10654-021-00752-6</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>440,000 participants. Pre-diagnostic SII, NLR, PLR associated with 4,237 breast cancer cases.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Prostate Cancer <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>Gradient boosting on 11 routine lab features achieved AUC 0.72. UK Biobank confirms pre-diagnostic associations. Among the least developed—requires larger datasets and external validation.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Satır A, et al. "Prediction of Prostate Cancer From Routine Laboratory Markers." <em>J Clin Lab Anal</em> 2025;39(3):e25143. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/jcla.25143" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1002/jcla.25143</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>GBM AUC 0.72 vs PSA alone 0.64. Adding CBC markers improves detection.</em></p></li>
<li>Watts EL, et al. "Hematologic Markers and Prostate Cancer Risk in UK Biobank." <em>Cancer Epidemiol Biomarkers Prev</em> 2020;29(8):1615–1626. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-19-1525" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1158/1055-9965.EPI-19-1525</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>209,686 men, 5,723 prostate cancer diagnoses. RBC, platelet count, MCH independently associated.</em></p></li>
<li>Li D, et al. "Prognostic value of serum alkaline phosphatase in prostate cancer." <em>Cancer Manag Res</em> 2018;10:3125–3139. <a href="https://doi.org/10.2147/CMAR.S174237" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.2147/CMAR.S174237</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Meta-analysis: high ALP associated with HR 1.74 for worse OS.</em></p></li>
<li>Gu X, et al. "Prognostic significance of NLR in prostate cancer: evidence from 16,266 patients." <em>Sci Rep</em> 2016;6:22089. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/srep22089" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/srep22089</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Elevated NLR predicts poor OS (HR 1.38) and PFS (HR 1.24).</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

