<h3>Non-Cancer Diseases</h3>

<div class="disease-accordion">

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Cardiovascular Disease <span class="status-validated">VALIDATED</span></summary>
<p>Multiple ML models on 6,800–378,000 patients consistently outperform Framingham and ACC/AHA Pooled Cohort Equations by 10–25%. No population-scale deployment using routine lab data has occurred.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Weng SF, et al. "Can Machine-Learning Improve Cardiovascular Risk Prediction Using Routine Clinical Data?" <em>PLOS One</em> 2017;12(4):e0174944. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0174944" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0174944</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Neural network AUC 0.764 vs PCE 0.728 on 378,256 patients. 355 additional events correctly identified per 100,000.</em></p></li>
<li>CTT Collaboration. "Efficacy and Safety of More Intensive Lowering of LDL Cholesterol." <em>Lancet</em> 2010;376(9753):1670–1681. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(10)61350-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(10)61350-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>26 statin trials (170,000 participants). 25–35% risk reduction per mmol/L LDL reduction.</em></p></li>
<li>Madjid M, Fatemi O. "Components of the CBC as Risk Predictors for Coronary Heart Disease." <em>Tex Heart Inst J</em> 2013;40(1):17–29. <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23467296/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23467296/</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>NLR, WBC subtypes, platelet indices independently predict coronary events.</em></p></li>
<li>Tonelli M, et al. "Relation Between RDW and Cardiovascular Event Rate." <em>Circulation</em> 2008;117(2):163–168. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.107.727545" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCULATIONAHA.107.727545</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>RDW &gt;14.5% predicts CV mortality HR 1.78, even in non-anemic subjects.</em></p></li>
<li>Ambale-Venkatesh B, et al. "Cardiovascular Event Prediction by Machine Learning: MESA." <em>Circ Res</em> 2017;121(9):1092–1101. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.117.311312" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.117.311312</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random survival forest on 6,814 participants over 12 years. Outperforms Framingham by 10–25%.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Type 2 Diabetes <span class="status-validated">VALIDATED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost on 448,277 UK Biobank participants achieves AUC 0.90. LightGBM on 2.1 million Ontario residents predicts onset up to 5 years before diagnosis. Validated across multiple large populations.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Razavian N, et al. "Population-Level Prediction of Type 2 Diabetes From Claims Data." <em>Big Data</em> 2015;3(4):277–287. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1089/big.2015.0020" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1089/big.2015.0020</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.80 predicting onset 3–5 years before diagnosis while values remained below thresholds.</em></p></li>
<li>Lugner et al. "Identifying Top Ten Predictors of Type 2 Diabetes Through ML Analysis of UK Biobank Data." <em>Sci Rep</em> 2024;14:2102. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-52023-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-52023-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.90 on 448,277 participants. 10-feature model achieves AUC 0.88.</em></p></li>
<li>Ravaut M, et al. "ML Model Using Administrative Health Data to Predict Onset of Type 2 Diabetes." <em>JAMA Netw Open</em> 2021;4(5):e2111315. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2021.11315" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2021.11315</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>2,137,343 Ontario residents. Largest population-scale ML diabetes prediction study.</em></p></li>
<li>Knowler WC, et al. "Reduction in Incidence of Type 2 Diabetes with Lifestyle Intervention or Metformin." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2002;346(6):393–403. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa012512" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa012512</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>DPP: 58% reduction with lifestyle intervention, 31% with metformin in prediabetic patients.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Chronic Kidney Disease <span class="status-deployed">DEPLOYED</span></summary>
<p>Klinrisk is the most advanced non-cancer algorithm. Validated on 4.8 million US adults (AUC 0.80–0.87) and CE-marked by Roche for the navify platform in October 2025.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Tangri N, et al. "Validation of the Klinrisk ML Model in the CANVAS Program and CREDENCE Trial." <em>Diabetes Obes Metab</em> 2024;26(8):3371–3380. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/dom.15678" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1111/dom.15678</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.88, outperforming KDIGO heatmap at every interval.</em></p></li>
<li>Tangri N, et al. "Validation of Klinrisk in a Large Representative US Population." <em>J Am Soc Nephrol</em> 2026;37(2):326–337. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1681/ASN.0000000817" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1681/ASN.0000000817</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>4.8 million US adults across commercial, Medicare, Medicaid. AUC 0.80–0.87.</em></p></li>
<li>Ferguson T, et al. "Development and External Validation of a ML Model for Progression of CKD." <em>Kidney Int Rep</em> 2022;7(8):1772–1781. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ekir.2022.05.004" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ekir.2022.05.004</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Klinrisk RSF on 77,196 + 107,097 patients. AUC 0.88 at two years.</em></p></li>
<li>Tangri N, et al. "Multinational Assessment of Accuracy of Equations for Predicting Risk of Kidney Failure." <em>JAMA</em> 2016;315(2):164–174. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2015.18202" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2015.18202</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>KFRE validated across 31 cohorts. eGFR slope and albuminuria as primary predictors.</em></p></li>
<li>Perkovic V, et al. "Canagliflozin and Renal Outcomes in Type 2 Diabetes and Nephropathy." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2019;380(24):2295–2306. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1811744" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1811744</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>CREDENCE: canagliflozin reduces kidney failure by 30%, CV events by 20%.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Heart Failure <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>Ensemble deep learning on 52,265 patients achieves AUC 0.91. Random forest on CBC alone achieves AUC 0.948. Prospective trajectory analysis confirms BNP, creatinine, and uric acid rise months before decompensation.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Pu J, et al. "Development and validation of a ML model for predicting risk of heart failure from routine blood test." <em>Front Cardiovasc Med</em> 2025;12:1539966. <a href="https://doi.org/10.3389/fcvm.2025.1539966" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.3389/fcvm.2025.1539966</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random forest on CBC alone. AUC 0.948 (226 patients—requires larger replication).</em></p></li>
<li>McGilvray MM, et al. "EHR-Based Deep Learning Prediction of Death or Severe Decompensation in Heart Failure." <em>JACC Heart Fail</em> 2022;10(9):637–647. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jchf.2022.05.010" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jchf.2022.05.010</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>52,265 patients. AUC 0.91. BNP, BUN, sodium, creatinine, hemoglobin as key features.</em></p></li>
<li>Nozaki A, et al. "Trajectories of Biomarkers Before and After Hospitalization for Heart Failure." <em>Circ J</em> 2026;90(2):185–192. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1253/circj.CJ-25-0824" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1253/circj.CJ-25-0824</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>BNP, creatinine, uric acid rise ~60 days before re-hospitalization.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Sepsis <span class="status-deployed">DEPLOYED</span></summary>
<p>TREWS is deployed across five Johns Hopkins hospitals with 18.7% mortality reduction. Dascena InSight, validated across 684,443 encounters (AUC 0.92), is FDA-cleared. Most clinically validated real-time application in this program.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Mao Q, et al. "Multicentre validation of a sepsis prediction algorithm using only vital sign data." <em>BMJ Open</em> 2018;8:e017833. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/bmjopen-2017-017833" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1136/bmjopen-2017-017833</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>InSight: AUC ~0.90 across 684,443 encounters. FDA-cleared.</em></p></li>
<li>Henry KE, et al. "A Targeted Real-Time Early Warning Score (TREWScore) for Septic Shock." <em>Sci Transl Med</em> 2015;7(299):299ra122. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1126/scitranslmed.aab3719" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1126/scitranslmed.aab3719</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.83 with median 28.2-hour lead time on ~69,000 ICU admissions.</em></p></li>
<li>Adams R, et al. "Prospective, Multi-Site Study of Patient Outcomes After Implementation of TREWS." <em>Nat Med</em> 2022;28(7):1455–1460. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41591-022-01894-0" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41591-022-01894-0</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>18.7% mortality reduction, 89% provider adoption, 82% sensitivity, 97% NPV.</em></p></li>
<li>Seymour CW, et al. "Derivation, Validation, and Potential Treatment Implications of Novel Clinical Phenotypes for Sepsis." <em>JAMA</em> 2019;321(20):2003–2017. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2019.5791" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2019.5791</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>4 ML-derived sepsis subtypes with mortality 5–39% using CBC/CMP variables.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Familial Hypercholesterolemia <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>FIND FH (AUC 0.94) and FAMCAT2 (AUC &gt;0.86 across 4 million UK patients). Fewer than 1% of estimated FH patients are currently diagnosed. FAMCAT2 is operational in the NHS Wessex region.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Banda JM, et al. "Finding missed cases of familial hypercholesterolemia using machine learning." <em>npj Digit Med</em> 2019;2:23. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41746-019-0101-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41746-019-0101-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>FIND FH: AUC 0.94, PPV 0.88. Applied to 170 million records, flagging 1.3 million likely cases.</em></p></li>
<li>Akyea RK, et al. "Supervised ML approaches in detecting familial hypercholesterolaemia in primary care." <em>npj Digit Med</em> 2020;3:142. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41746-020-00349-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41746-020-00349-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>FAMCAT2 on 4,027,775 patients. AUC &gt;0.87. Deployed in NHS Wessex via EMIS system.</em></p></li>
<li>Hesse R, et al. "FH Identification by ML Using Lipid Profile Data." <em>Circ Genom Precis Med</em> 2022;15(5):e003324. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCGEN.121.003324" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1161/CIRCGEN.121.003324</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.754–0.856 from lipid profile alone, outperforming LDL-C threshold.</em></p></li>
<li>Luirink IK, et al. "20-Year Follow-up of Statins in Children with FH." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 2019;381(16):1547–1556. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1816454" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMoa1816454</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Early statin: 1% CV events by age 39 vs 26% in untreated parents.</em></p></li>
<li>Versmissen J, et al. "Efficacy of statins in familial hypercholesterolaemia." <em>BMJ</em> 2008;337:a2423. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.a2423" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.a2423</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>76% reduction in CHD risk with statin treatment in 2,146 FH patients.</em></p></li>
<li>Ference BA, et al. "The LDL cumulative exposure hypothesis." <em>Nat Rev Cardiol</em> 2024;21:701–716. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41569-024-01039-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41569-024-01039-5</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Each year of delayed diagnosis inflicts irreversible arterial damage.</em></p></li>
<li>Vaseghi G, et al. "Hematological Inflammatory Markers in FH Patients." <em>Biomed Res Int</em> 2022;2022(1):5051434. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1155/2022/5051434" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1155/2022/5051434</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Normal triglycerides as critical negative discriminator in the FH lipid signature.</em></p></li>
<li>Khera AV, et al. "Diagnostic Yield and Clinical Utility of Sequencing FH Genes." <em>J Am Coll Cardiol</em> 2016;67(22):2578–2589. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2016.03.520" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacc.2016.03.520</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Among LDL-C ≥190, &lt;2% carry monogenic FH mutation; 55% of carriers have LDL-C below 190. ML corrects both failures.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Hemochromatosis <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost achieved AUC 0.94 on HEIRS family study data. Patients treated before cirrhosis achieve normal life expectancy—one of the highest-value, lowest-cost interventions.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Martins Conde P, et al. "Efficient ML-Based Approach for Screening Individuals at Risk of Hereditary Haemochromatosis." <em>Sci Rep</em> 2020;10:20613. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-020-77367-6" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-020-77367-6</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.94 using ferritin, transferrin saturation, MCV, ALT, AST. Outperforms IRON screening score.</em></p></li>
<li>Adams PC, et al. "Screening for Iron Overload: Lessons from the HEIRS Study." <em>Can J Gastroenterol</em> 2009;23(11):769–772. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1155/2009/839308" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1155/2009/839308</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>&gt;100,000 individuals screened. Transferrin saturation sensitivity 75% for C282Y homozygotes.</em></p></li>
<li>Niederau C, et al. "Survival and Causes of Death in Cirrhotic and Noncirrhotic Patients with Primary Hemochromatosis." <em>N Engl J Med</em> 1985;313(20):1256–1262. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJM198511143132004" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJM198511143132004</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Treated before cirrhosis: normal life expectancy. After: 219-fold liver cancer risk, 306-fold cardiomyopathy risk.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Hypothyroidism <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>Multi-institutional study achieved AUC 0.909 from routine blood parameters. Subclinical hypothyroidism affects 4–8% of adults with 18–28% increased coronary risk.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Hu M, et al. "ML System for Thyroid Dysfunction Diagnosis Based on Routine Laboratory Tests." <em>Commun Med</em> 2022;2:9. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/s43856-022-00071-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1038/s43856-022-00071-1</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.909 for hypothyroidism from 11 routine tests without thyroid function tests. Top predictors: creatinine, LDH, total cholesterol.</em></p></li>
<li>Wopereis DM, et al. "The Relation Between Thyroid Function and Anemia." <em>J Clin Endocrinol Metab</em> 2018;103(10):3658–3667. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1210/jc.2018-00481" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1210/jc.2018-00481</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>OR 1.84 for anemia in overt hypothyroidism. CBC hemoglobin as detectable component.</em></p></li>
<li>Rodondi N, et al. "Subclinical Hypothyroidism and the Risk of Coronary Heart Disease and Mortality." <em>JAMA</em> 2010;304(12):1365–1374. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2010.1361" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.2010.1361</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>55,287 participants. 18–28% increased CHD events with subclinical hypothyroidism (TSH 7–10).</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>NAFLD / Liver Fibrosis <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost achieves AUC 0.91 for advanced fibrosis, outperforming FIB-4 (0.78) and NFS (0.81). NAFLD affects 38% of US adults—one of the largest addressable populations.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Dabbah S, et al. "ML Algorithms to Screen for Advanced Liver Fibrosis in MASLD." <em>Digestion</em> 2025;106(3):189–202. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1159/000542241" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1159/000542241</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>AUC 0.91 vs FIB-4 (0.78) and NFS (0.81) in 618 biopsy-confirmed patients.</em></p></li>
<li>Sterling RK, et al. "Development of a Simple Noninvasive Index to Predict Significant Fibrosis." <em>Hepatology</em> 2006;43(6):1317–1325. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/hep.21178" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1002/hep.21178</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Original FIB-4 derivation. AUC 0.80 for advanced fibrosis. Clinical baseline for ML comparison.</em></p></li>
<li>Lim DYZ, et al. "ML to Predict Onset of NAFLD in an All-Comers Cohort." <em>Gastro Hep Adv</em> 2024;3(7):1005–1011. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gastha.2024.06.007" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.gastha.2024.06.007</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Random survival forest on 25,599 patients predicting time-to-NAFLD onset from routine labs.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Wilson's Disease <span class="status-published">PUBLISHED</span></summary>
<p>XGBoost on 3,559 patients achieves AUC 0.78–0.82 for liver failure prediction. Limited PPV of ceruloplasmin alone supports multi-marker ML approaches.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Liang C, et al. "Predicting Wilson's Disease Progression Using ML with Real-World EHR." <em>medRxiv</em> 2023. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1101/2023.07.28.23293309" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1101/2023.07.28.23293309</a> (preprint)<p class="ref-annotation"><em>3,559 WD patients from Optum EHR. Dynamic AUC 0.78–0.82.</em></p></li>
<li>Cauza E, et al. "Screening for Wilson's Disease by Serum Ceruloplasmin." <em>J Hepatol</em> 1997;27(2):358–362. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/s0168-8278(97)80182-1" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/s0168-8278(97)80182-1</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>Ceruloplasmin alone has limited PPV. Low-ALP-with-elevated-bilirubin is the key ML discriminator.</em></p></li>
<li>Chen K, et al. "Liver Cirrhosis Prediction for Patients with Wilson Disease Based on ML." <em>Eur J Gastroenterol Hepatol</em> 2022;34(10):1067–1073. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/MEG.0000000000002424" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1097/MEG.0000000000002424</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>346 WD patients. Routine hematological parameters predict cirrhosis beyond clinical thresholds.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Addison's Disease <span class="status-signal">SIGNAL ONLY</span></summary>
<p>No ML model exists for human Addison's disease. Proof-of-concept from veterinary medicine: AdaBoost achieves &gt;99% accuracy on canine hypoadrenocorticism using the same biochemistry. Human blood signature (hyponatremia in 84%, elevated TSH in 52%) is well-documented.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Reagan KL, et al. "Machine Learning Algorithm as a Diagnostic Tool for Hypoadrenocorticism in Dogs." <em>Domest Anim Endocrinol</em> 2020;72:106396. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.domaniend.2019.106396" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.domaniend.2019.106396</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>&gt;99% accuracy in &gt;1,000 dogs. Canine physiology essentially identical to human Addison's.</em></p></li>
<li>Sævik ÅB, et al. "Clues for Early Detection of Autoimmune Addison's Disease—Myths and Realities." <em>J Intern Med</em> 2018;283(2):190–199. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/joim.12699" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1111/joim.12699</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>247 patients: hyponatremia in 84%, elevated TSH in 52%, hyperkalemia in only 33%. Hyponatremia is the dominant signal.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

<details class="disease-detail"><summary>Primary Biliary Cholangitis <span class="status-signal">SIGNAL ONLY</span></summary>
<p>No dedicated ML classification model exists. ALP and bilirubin are validated as surrogate endpoints in a 4,845-patient meta-analysis. The persistent ALP elevation pattern is well-characterized but no ML model has been built.</p>
<ol class="disease-refs">
<li>Siddiqui MS, et al. "Diagnostic Accuracy of Noninvasive Fibrosis Models to Detect Change in Fibrosis Stage." <em>Clin Gastroenterol Hepatol</em> 2019;17(9):1877–1885. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cgh.2018.12.031" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cgh.2018.12.031</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>ALP-containing markers achieve AUC 0.82 for fibrosis detection. Supports PBC-specific model feasibility.</em></p></li>
<li>Lammers WJ, et al. "Levels of ALP and Bilirubin Are Surrogate End Points of Outcomes in Primary Biliary Cirrhosis." <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2014;147(6):1338–1349.e5. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2014.08.029" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2014.08.029</a><p class="ref-annotation"><em>4,845 PBC patients from 15 cohorts. ALP normalization on UDCA = population-equivalent survival.</em></p></li>
</ol>
</details>

